% java DooBee
DooBeeDooBeeDo
Fill in the missing code: 
public class DooBee {
 public static void main (String[] args) {
 int x = 1;
 while (x < _____ ) {
 System.out._________(“Doo”);
 System.out._________(“Bee”);
 x = x + 1;
 }
 if (x == ______ ) {
 System.out.print(“Do”);
 }
 }
}

System.out.print vs. 
System.out.println
If you’ve been paying attention (of 
course you have) then you’ve noticed us 
switching between print and println.
Did you spot the difference?
System.out.println inserts a newline 
(think of println as printnewline while 
System.out.print keeps printing to 
the same line. If you want each thing 
you print out to be on its own line, use 
println. If you want everything to stick 
together on one line, use print.

